    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Missile-Free Russia</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ralph Kessler letter rejects Geoffrey E Forden suggestion that US pay $160 million to get Russia's early-warning satellites functioning so it will not launch missiles in error; says Russia should scrap its atomic hardware and take care of its people</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Geoffrey E. Forden (Op-Ed, Sept. 6) suggests that the United States pay $160 million to get Russia's early-warning satellites functioning so it won't launch missiles in error. Russia is a helpless giant, and life for its people gets worse every day. Why does it, as he says, have missiles ready to launch on a few minutes' notice and targeted against the United States?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Geoffrey E. Forden (Op-Ed, Sept. 6) suggests that the United States pay $160 million to get Russia's early-warning satellites functioning so it won't launch missiles in error. Russia is a helpless giant, and life for its people gets worse every day. Why does it, as he says, have missiles ready to launch on a few minutes' notice and targeted against the United States?</p>
        <p>Russia should instead do what Ukraine did: scrap its atomic hardware and try to take care of its people.</p>
        <p>RALPH KESSLER  Berkeley, Calif., Sept. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
